Rating: 4
Okay, so I didn't use this recipe EXACTLY, but the basic idea was there and mine was a LOT easier. I used pre-made pie crusts from Trader Joe's and they were fantastic! For the filling, I used a 1lb. ground sirloin (80/20 for a little fat) instead of skirt steak. Obviously MUCH easier to use. First I sauted 2 small onions with an equal amount of diced carrots until they were nice and caramelly. (Side note - the Vidalia Onion Chopper is a wonder with getting veggies like that cut in a jiffy). I then added the wine in and let it reduce and then removed the veggies. I then added in the ground beef (crumbled up) and let it just sit on one side for a good 5-10 minutes to give it that nice rich dark brown color and great taste. Then I grated in 2 cloves of garlic, cooked it until it was done and added the veggies back in - oh yes, I salted and peppered both the veggies and beef towards the end of their cooking. Then 1 tbl. of flour to the entire mixture - cook about a minute. Then add 1/2 cup beef broth and 2 tbl. Worcestershire sauce (or only one if you're not crazy about Wors. sauce). I also added the thyme, but all I had was ground. Then you just cut the pie round in half and spoon the mixture on 1/2 that crust, sprinkle blue cheese if you want it and fold the crust over your mixture so you get a sort of round triangle. Use the edge of a fork to press the two open sides together. Cut a slit in the top and brush with an egg wash. In the oven at 400 for about 10-20 minutes until the crust is golden brown. My family LOVED, LOVED, LOVED this recipe I will keep it as a staple in our house. BTW my recipe made 6 pasties. They are very rich and hearty so one should be plenty per person. Serve with something light, like fresh green beans or a salad. NO potatoes as it would be a very heavy meal.

Rating: 3
The filling is excellent! I confess I used my English mother-in-law's shortcrust pastry recipe (butter + lard) rather than the one listed here (as this one looked to be too flaky for my husband's taste), but the result was scrumptious.

Rating: 3
I would try this recipe again, but would add all of the blue cheese next time. (I only added about half because I thought that it would be too much and over-power the rest of the filling.) Needless to say, it turns out that the entire portion of blue cheese truly compliments the delightful caramelized onion in white wine (I used a bargain Pinot Grigio) and Thyme. Wow, what flavor! Also, the edge of the crust was too heavy for me so I'll leave less crust on the edge and also be sure to brush the egg white only as a glue along the seem. (It changed the consistency with a less than soft shell as I remember my mother making these when I was little and she used white flour and simply pinched the seem on the outer edge only to leave a slight crust.) I bought outstanding rib eye from the butcher (DD Meats, ML Terrace...for all you Seattle natives) which I still cut into 1/4" pieces...it cooked perfectly in 30 min. I served this meal with steamed broccoli. (I have a no-fail steaming technique of placing it on a plate for 3 minutes with a ceramic, microwave-safe bowl covering it and about a 1/4 cup of water on the plate. I nuked it just before the pasties were due.) Good times. Enjoy, all! Krista

