Rating: 3
I made these for an English friend for lunch but I made some changes for authenticity. To begin with I felt like the crust asked for way too much moisture so I avoided that but then realized afterward that you need the crust to be a bit tougher than what a pie requires because you should be able to pick up the pasty and eat it with your hands. My crust ended up way too flaky to do this. I used only spelt flour for dietery reasons and just reduced the moisture. Next time I'll add more water to give the dough more cohesion. In regards to the filling, I made the onion mixture exactly but I added an extra tablespoon of pepper. I used ground lamb instead of skirt steak because I had some around. No you don't cook the meat prior to stuffing it so if you are using the skirt steak, make sure you slice it somewhat thinly. The ground lamb turned out perfectly. I substituted bleu cheese for the stilton and I ended up only putting it in mine as the flavor was too strong for the lamb. I also blanched one large sweet potato (for dietary reasons but you can use a regular potato), roughly peeled it and then chopped it into cubes. Overall, it turned out wonderful and my friend really enjoyed it and said it was very authentic tasting except it needed more pepper as the real version is quite peppery.

